window.docContents[10].resolve({"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Algebraic-and-transcendental-numbers/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Algebraic-and-transcendental-numbers--Liouville-Numbers":{"contents":"A real number  is a Liouville number (Liouville) if for every  there exist\nintegers  with  such that\n\nIn Lean the strict positivity is encoded as . Thus a Liouville number is approximable by\nrationals to every order — far better than Dirichlet's universal order \n().\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence\u0009Algebraic and transcendental numbers","header":"9.6.2. Liouville Numbers","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Algebraic-and-transcendental-numbers/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Algebraic-and-transcendental-numbers--Liouville-Numbers"},"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Forthcoming-in-mathlib":{"contents":"The node below is an informal statement of a result that is the subject of an open mathlib pull\nrequest (the t-number-theory queue, as of June 2026). It carries a pr_url pointing at the live PR\nand no (lean := …) reference: the declarations are not yet in mathlib v4.30.0-rc2. It connects\ninto the dependency graph through the mathlib-backed transcendence and Diophantine-approximation nodes\nof this chapter via {uses} edges, and should be re-pointed to (lean := …) once the PR merges.\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence","header":"9.8. Forthcoming in mathlib","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Forthcoming-in-mathlib"},"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series":{"contents":"The nodes in this section are informal: the NewtonPolys project\n(CBirkbeck/NewtonPoly, main branch) is built against\nmathlib v4.28.0-rc1 and therefore carries no (lean := …) reference in this v4.30 chapter. Each node\nrecords the declaration that formalises it, an exact-source permalink at the project's recorded commit\na6d9970, and the true Lean status (the file is sorry-free). The cross-chapter edges to\n and  reflect genuine dependence: the Newton polygon of\na -adic power series is built from the valuation () of its coefficients, and\nits slopes encode the -adic valuations () of the roots. Following Gouvêa\n§7.4, the project abstracts a power series to its valuation sequence and proves the geometric\n\"supporting line\" facts and the radius-of-convergence theorem; the root-distribution functions are\ndefined but the root-counting theorem itself is recorded only as Gouvêa-cited motivation, not as a\nproved statement.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence","header":"9.7. Newton polygons of p-adic power series","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series"},"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/The-L-function-of-a-Weierstrass-curve/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--The-L-function-of-a-Weierstrass-curve--The-Local-Polynomial":{"contents":"Let  be a discrete valuation ring with residue field  of cardinality , and\n a Weierstrass curve over its fraction field (). The local\npolynomial of  is, in terms of the reduction type of the minimal model\n(),\n\nwhere  counts the points of the reduction\n(). The local Euler factor is the arithmetic function\nobtained from the inverse power series of this polynomial.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Elliptic Curves and Arithmetic Geometry\u0009The L-function of a Weierstrass curve","header":"7.9.1. The Local Polynomial","id":"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/The-L-function-of-a-Weierstrass-curve/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--The-L-function-of-a-Weierstrass-curve--The-Local-Polynomial"}});